Pantheon Mapping

I could see these becoming complementary navigation doctrines:

Pace Count

* Checksum
* Procedures
* Metrics
* Dead reckoning
* Precision

Terrain Navigation

* Spy
* Spider
* Semantic LiDAR
* Comparative Distillation
* Signalying
* Intuition informed by observation

One isn’t superior to the other. Skilled navigation comes from switching between them.

You might use pace count to cross a featureless stretch where landmarks are scarce, then transition to terrain association once distinctive features reappear. Likewise, in reasoning, sometimes you need careful, sequential accounting; other times it’s more effective to orient yourself by the broader structure of the problem and let that guide your next move.

That interplay fits well with one of your recurring Pantheon principles—Resolution Modulation. You change the resolution and navigation mode to match the terrain instead of insisting on a single strategy everywhere.